 Peter de Skydemore in 1216. The same manor was held by Godfrey Escudamore shortly after 1150. The Scudamore family claim descent from Ralph, recorded in Domesday Book (1086) as holder of <i>Opeton</i> (Upton), whose son was known as Reginald <i>Escudemor</i>."]}]},{"name":"Jenkin","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, which is derived from the medieval given name <i>Jankin</i>. This was a pet form of the boy's name   Jan  , with the diminutive suffix <i>-kin</i>. The modern given name is popular in Wales, where the surnames <i>Jenkin</i> and <i>Jenkins</i> are common."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":2,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":47,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Jenkin Scudamore was born about 1335, in Kentchurch, Herefordshire, England, his father, Sir John Scudamore, was 31 and his mother, Joyce Marbury, was 22. He had at least 3 sons with Elizabeth ferch Owain Glendower."},"et":{"Abt 1335–":"umbes 1335–Surnud","1335–1409":"1335–1409","1335–Male":"1335–Surnud","1342–Male":"1342–Surnud","1344–Female":"1344–Surnud","1346–Female":"1346–Surnud","1348–Female":"1348–Surnud","1370–1416":"1370–1416","1375–1434":"1375–1434","1383–1434":"1383–1434","1385–Male":"1385–Surnud","130